<TEXT>
city officials have asked for reports on whether 
police prevented fire department divers from joining the search for 
a victim trapped in a sightseeing helicopter that crashed and sank 
in the east river 
a fire lieutenant was quoted as saying he had eight divers at 
the scene sunday morning but police kept them away at a time when 
only two police divers were in the water 
it took 90 minutes to find the helicopter in the rivers murk 
and free the trapped passenger takashi oyama a japanese 
businessman oyama 29 was taken to bellevue hospital where he 
died nine hours later 
the pilot and three other passengers none seriously injured 
escaped to the surface and were taken to hospitals 
the national transportation safety board also said it would look 
into the issue of whether rescue was impeded by policefirefighter 
rivalry if it received information that such a dispute had occurred 
police commissioner benjamin ward said two police divers were in 
the water by 1037 am 14 minutes after the first report of the 
crash by 1045 nine divers were conducting a pattern search of 
the area he said 
fire commissioner joseph bruno said two fire department divers 
were there at 1037 and that eight were on the scene by 1045 
ward dismissed as a personal opinion an earlier statement by 
fire lt patrick brown of rescue co 1 that the search was impeded 
because his divers were not allowed to join it 
it was the feeling of the police commander on the scene and in 
fact the common practice of all experienced water rescuers that 
uncoordinated search teams in the water at the same time is 
dangerous and unproductive ward said in explaining why the fire 
departments offer was declined 
bruno said the rescue effort was within the purview of the 
police department and i have no problem with that i do have a 
problem with reports saying we are not needed and unnecessary our 
feeling is that if resources were available they should be 
utilized 
mayor edward i koch said he has asked for a report to find 
out whether all of the assistance on the scene was properly used 
the mayor said he would not speculate before he got the 
information 
in line with rules laid down by koch last year to end 
jurisdiction disputes police were in charge at sundays crash 
site a nonfire emergency the fire department calls the shots at 
fire emergencies 
first deputy mayor stanley brezenoff said the only question is 
were there enough divers in the water to make the rescue without 
using fire divers 
the crashed helicopter a bell jet ranger operated by island 
helicopter corp of garden city plunged from 1400 feet after a 
15to20minute tour of manhattan 
frank ghiorsi chief of the federal safety boards new york 
office said particular attention would be given seat belts and the 
pontoons which separated from the craft on impact 
oyama was snarled in his belt and had to be cut free said 
michael rivadeneyra one of divers who found the helicopter in 35 
feet of water 
