<TEXT>
image is everything in the roughandtumble world 
of chicago politics says mayor eugene sawyer but after four 
months surrounded by the trappings of power he admits his image 
isnt what it should be 
his enemies gripe about his willingness to reward friends and 
his friends gripe about his unwillingness to punish enemies 
i might become a little more aggressive harder than i used to 
be but thats because the job will make me so the softspoken 
mayor said during a recent interview 
everything you do or say in this office is political or 
somebody will couch it that way and force you to respond in a 
political manner you try to be a statesman but hey you better be 
a politician too he added otherwise you wont be around very 
long 
people have all kinds of plans for you and i just say that if 
im going to make a mistake it will be one i made myself not 
something that somebody suggested to me said sawyer 58 
sawyer became embroiled in a new controversy this weekend when 
religious leaders accused mayoral community liaison aide steve 
cokely of repeatedly using racial and religious slurs against jews 
and christians in a series of taperecorded lectures to followers 
of nation of islam leader louis farrakhan 
mayoral spokesman monroe anderson said sawyer planned to ask 
cokely 35 to tune down his rhetoric but did not plan to fire 
him 
sawyer became mayor following the death in november of harold 
washington who became the citys first black mayor in 1983 and had 
consolidated his power over the cook county democratic party 
washington had served only eight months of his second term and 
sawyer must at some point face an election if he wants to stay in 
office but the date of the next mayoral election is up in the air 
the chicago board of election commissioners ruled last week that 
an election would be held in 1989 if city clerk walter kozubowski 
declared the mayors office vacant kozubowski said he wouldnt do 
so unless ordered by a court 
his opposition virtually assures the controversy will be 
resolved in court already competing lawsuits arguing for either a 
1989 or 1991 election are pending 
sawyer has said he is prepared to run whenever the next election 
is scheduled 
no matter what the date observers say the absence of a 
political giant like washington or the late mayor richard j daley 
will show how splintered this citys oncevaunted democratic 
machine has become 
therell be so many people running black white green 
that nobody will know what to do said black activist lu palmer 
credited with organizing the grassroots campaign that elected 
washington to his first term 
and theres scores of people talking about running for 
everything from dogcatcher to mayor and nobodys got the power to 
tell them no he continued 
machines move with precision if there was a chief like 
harold things would still be done with precision he said but 
now youve got a lot of little chieftains and everybodys throwing 
things in the way 
sawyer has had a difficult time shouldering the mantle since he 
was elected by a city council coalition made up mostly of white 
antiwashington aldermen 
some people were with harold because they believed in him 
some because they feared him and some because he proved he could 
win said alderman danny davis 
everybody knew there would be some slippage after he died 
added davis but nobody knew how much 
the coalition that put sawyer in office already has shown a 
tendency to fray at the seams his bloc held together long enough 
to pass washingtons record budget but grumbling set in almost 
immediately afterward and many of sawyers legislative proposals 
are languishing in the council 
and during the primary elections in march several black 
aldermen who were among sawyers most identifiable supporters got 
clobbered in races for party committeeman positions normally 
aldermen are shooins for those posts 
what that told me is that the voters in my ward dont like 
him said william beavers one of the aldermen and they may 
not be crazy about me standing behind him either 
</TEXT>
