<TEXT>
except for the thunder of aircraft 
taking off and the showers of flares overhead soviet soldiers 
serving at a base near kabul airport could almost convince 
themselves they are in the soviet union 
the corrugated metal huts and wooden barracks are typical of 
bases in their native land 
beside each cot in the bunkhouses are tubes of soviet 
toothpaste soviet soap and soviet mirrors purchased at the base 
store 
russian women like oksana okulova serve breakfast lunch and 
dinner to the soldiers on soviet crockery afterward the women 
wash up while the men go off to train afghan government troops and 
help them defend the city against attack by anticommunist rebels 
the hearty breads cherished by soviets are baked at the base 
each day and familiar foods like ham cheese and apples are flown 
in for the soldiers who eschew the spicy afghan dishes 
but the flares which are released by aircraft to deflect 
heatseeking stinger missiles serve as a reminder that the 
soldiers are in danger even inside the closely guarded confines of 
the base 
of course its dangerous flying here tiit tommela an army 
major from soviet estonia told visiting foreign journalists we 
have to take precautions against your stingers 
afghan guerrillas who have been fighting the prosoviet 
government for 10 years use the ussupplied missiles effectively 
against government aircraft 
ms okulova a 25yearold who sought an escape from the 
industrial russian city of voronezh said the aviation dangers are 
the only aspect of her life in afghanistan she finds frightening 
we hardly ever leave the base so its easy to just keep 
occupied and not think about the fact that there is a war going 
on she said we are forbidden to go to the markets and when 
we go on touring trips we travel as a group 
officers refused to say how many soldiers serve at the sprawling 
complex that provides security for the capital kabul and the 
aircraft serving it it appears to house at least 1000 soviets 
on saturday as the noon sun burst through rainclouds in the 
mountains ringing kabul a squad of soviet paratroopers in 
camouflage jumpsuits lined up on the sports field to teach afghans 
the art of handtohand combat 
nearby soldiers worked with two german shepherds trained to 
sniff out explosives hidden in items like canteens and matchboxes 
there are occasional problems with the men ms okulova 
admitted when asked how she and several dozen other service workers 
deal with so many lonely soldiers far from home 
but several factors limit the potential for romantic problems 
strict rules forbid intimate relationships there is little privacy 
in the dormitories and barracks and the women must work long 
hours mrs okulova said 
the soviets plan to start pulling out of afghanistan on may 15 
under an accord signed last month in geneva however the kabul 
base may be one of the last closed by the soviets 
because there is no firm exit date the soldiers at the base 
have a businessasusual attitude although they admit to being 
eager to return home 
we will go when we are told to go said alexander alexandrov 
of the ukrainian city of kharkov everything here is normal for 
the time being although we are of course happy that a settlement 
has been reached in geneva 
soviet soldiers intervened in december 1979 to support the 
government and about 115000 remain in afghanistan 
in keeping with moscows official contention that afghanistans 
army is now strong enough to defend the country without soviet 
fighting power the soldiers had high praise for the forces loyal 
to president najib 
they will resolve their own problems said andrei tarelkin 
a paratrooper from the russian city of ivanovo he was one of 
several decorated heroes turned out in full parade uniform saturday 
for the benefit of the visitors 
the afghan army is young but it should be able to defend 
itself 
some western observers here expect the rebel forces based in 
pakistan to move north and take control of parts of afghanistan as 
the soviets retreat najibs regular army numbers only about 40000 
soldiers many of them underage conscripts likely to flee if 
government positions becomes indefensible 
</TEXT>
