<TEXT>
after years of being considered the little 
sibling of broadcast television some say the cable tv industry is 
beginning to look more like goliath than david 
cable tv now watched by more than 50 percent of all american 
households has become a 12 billion industry that is gaining 
viewers steadily mostly at the expense of the broadcast networks 
but with prosperity comes increased scrutiny and in cables 
case congress has been raising questions about concentration of 
ownership within the industry complaints of poor service and 
rising rates some in congress say it may be time to reregulate 
cable tv 
we have to pay attention to this james p mooney president 
of the national cable television association told an audience at 
the opening session of the groups annual convention sunday 
we cant rebuff our friends he said an important part of 
good business is good politics 
more than 13000 people are expected to attend the convention 
which runs through tuesday 
most governmental regulation has been lifted from the industry 
the most recent deregulation came in january 1987 when most cable 
systems were freed of municipal rate control they now have more 
control than ever on what viewers see and how much they pay 
deregulation brought increases in rates the industry says the 
average subscribers bill rose 67 percent in the first six months 
after price control was lifted but critics in congress cite 
instances of rates going up by as much as 400 percent in some 
systems 
despite the increase subscribers continued to sign on cable 
systems added more than 4 million subscribers in 1987 putting the 
percentage of households receiving cable to nearly 52 percent 
about 45 million households 
now that many cable companies have finished building their 
systems wiring more than 80 percent of the nations households 
cable companies are starting to pay off their debt and are putting 
their cash into programming 
programming is going to drive penetration said james s 
cownie president of heritage communications of des moines iowa 
and ncta chairman 
thats going to move us up to the 70 percent saturation level 
from 52 percent where we are now 
the industry has been encouraged by the success of its early 
