<TEXT>
coalingas downtown business district 
devastated five years ago by one of californias strongest 
earthquakes this century is still struggling to recover 
in one terrifying moment the towns turnofthecentury stores 
buckled under the force of the quake 
the 67magnitude temblor on may 2 1983 dealt its heaviest 
toll to two blocks that held most of the communitys retail stores 
all had to be razed 
today on the same land modern onestory block buildings house 
the merchants who hung on during the hard times after the quake in 
the town of 8000 residents about 200 miles southeast of san 
francisco 
but vacant lots also mark much of downtown raising concern that 
there are too few shops left to attract enough customers to be 
profitable 
if there were other businesses things would be working 
tremendously there are too many empty lots said marjorie kerr 
who moved all the clothes from her dress shop to her lessdamaged 
home after the earthquake until she could get back in business 
first in a gymnasium then a house trailer and now in the 
rejuvenated downtown 
downtown businesses now include two dress shops two banks two 
drug stores a furniture store a combination bicyclecomputer shop 
and a sears mail order store other downtown offices house a weekly 
newspaper a lawyer accountant and real estate agent 
there are no coffee shops so people dont come downtown as 
much said mrs kerr we need more retail in these two blocks 
not offices 
the city government which aggressively secured a variety of 
financing to recover from the quake owns the rebuilt stores and is 
trying to find more financing and more businesses to fill the empty 
lots 
the city subsidizes rents charging about 34 cents a square 
foot said glen adams a councilman and chamber of commerce 
director thats a sharp increase from the 1020 cents per square 
foot merchants paid for space in the structures wiped out by the 
quake 
those increases make survival difficult for store owners who 
were just making it under the old rents mrs kerr said the owners 
of a jewelry store decided to retire after the earthquake a 
television store closed and one business owner died of stress while 
struggling to keep going in a house trailer 
not all merchants have been hurt however the operators of 
service pharmacy owned their building and it was fully insured 
enabling them to rebuild large enough for their needs and allow 
space to rent out offices 
sales taxes which indicate how much retail business a community 
is doing havent climbed back to the level before the earthquake 
which left 47 injured and caused an estimated 31 million in 
damage said alan jacobsen the public works director 
but 2873 building permits were issued in the five years since 
for 41 million worth of new construction or rehabilitation he 
said 
thats about one permit per building in town jacobsen said 
there has been a net gain of 384 dwellings in coalinga since the 
earthquake allowing the population to increase from 7000 to 
8000 jacobsen said 
the city also has a new natural gas system new sewer lines a 
new fire station bus terminal day care center senior citizens 
center fitness center and community swimming pool 
despite the personal and financial trauma jacobsen feels the 
earthquake was a real positive thing in making us clean up some 
problems we had in buildings safety and that type of thing 
the quake was one of californias 10 strongest quakes this 
century 
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on 
seismographs the san francisco earthquake of 1906 which occurred 
before the richter scale was devised has been estimated at 83 on 
the richter scale 
