the court said it will review a ruling that limited access by 
canadian officials to financial records of two canadian citizens 
with bank accounts in washington state 
the canadian department of national revenue the equivalent of 
the internal revenue service here sought records of philip stuart 
and mons kapoor both canadian citizens have accounts with the 
northwestern commercial bank in bellingham wash 
the canadian officials said they are investigating the two mens 
tax liability for 1980 1981 and 1982 
the officials sought the help of the us government under a 
1942 treaty between the two nations and the irs issued summonses 
to the bank in 1984 
stuart and kapoor then asked a federal judge to block the 
summonses the judge declined but the 9th us circuit court of 
appeals ruled in their favor last year 
the appeals court ordered the bank records withheld unless us 
officials state the canadian tax investigation has not reached a 
stage analogous to one in this country in which the irs would refer 
the case to the justice department for criminal prosecution 
we do not believe that requiring the irs to make such a 
statement will unduly restrict the services summonsing authority 
or impede enforcement of summonses the appeals court said 
but administration lawyers said the ruling could hinder us 
treaty obligations and impair the ability of investigators here to 
obtain foreign financial records 
the ruling requires a treaty partners tax investigation to 
meet standards grounded in domestic policies that have no 
application in the treaty partners jurisdiction the 
governments appeal said 
it unnecessarily hinders investigations that the united states 
has pledged by treaty to assist and that are entirely proper under 
the laws of the treaty partner the appeal added 
the united states has such tax treaties with 31 foreign 
governments and also exchanges information under other agreements 
reached with carribean basin nations 
the case is us vs stuart 871064 
