<TEXT>
orders to us factories for manufactured 
goods climbed 16 percent in march the biggest increase in three 
months the commerce department said today 
the department said that orders for durable and nondurable 
goods rose to a seasonally adjusted 21608 billion in march the 
best showing since a 2 percent rise in december 
the march advance represented surprising strength especially 
since the government had reported 10 days ago in a preliminary 
report that orders for durable goods had remained frozen in march 
that was changed today to show a healthy 1 percent increase 
reflecting newfound demand in orders for primary metals and 
machinery and in the transportation sector 
the 16 percent overall increase followed no change in february 
and a slight 06 percent drop in january 
during the first two months of the year many businesses cut 
back on orders in an effort to reduce a large buildup of unsold 
goods 
originally there was concern that the big rise in unsold goods 
that had occurred in the last three months of 1987 would topple the 
country into a recession especially if jittery consumers stopped 
buying bigticket items following the oct 19 stock market collapse 
these fears proved unwarranted however as a rebound in 
consumer spending helped propel the overall economy to healthy 
growth at an annual rate of 23 percent in the first three months 
of the year 
the 16 percent march increase in factory orders was aided in 
part by a 174 percent surge in demand for military equipment 
which rose to 1004 billion without this big defense buildup the 
overall orders increase would have been a smaller 1 percent 
the key category of nondefense capital goods fell 38 percent 
to 325 billion despite the setback analysts are still looking 
for this sector to show strength this year as us businesses boost 
spending on expansion projects to meet rising demand 
orders for transportation equipment climbed 34 percent while 
orders for primary metals such as steel were up 61 percent and 
orders for nonelectrical machinery advanced 21 percent 
orders for nondurable goods items not expected to last three 
years rose 23 percent to 1006 billion 
shipments of manufactured goods increased 26 percent to a 
record high of 2144 billion following a 08 percent february 
increase 
in a separate report the commerce department said that 
construction spending rose 15 percent in march the biggest 
increase since april 1987 
the advance was led by a 54 percent surge in spending on 
government building projects which climbed to an annual rate of 
823 billion 81 percent higher than a year ago 
