<TEXT>
the efficiency of the nations businesses in 
churning out goods and services improved at an annual rate of 09 
percent in the first quarter of 1988 nearly reversing a 
deterioration of 1 percent in the last three months of 1987 the 
government said today 
despite an increase of nearly a million new jobs from january 
through march nonfarm businesses raised the total number of hours 
worked by only 17 percent while achieving a 27 percent increase 
in output 
and for the first time since late 1986 workers overall are 
keeping up with inflation the labor department said 
wages and benefits increased at an annual rate of 34 percent in 
the first quarter raising the labor costs associated with each 
service or product by 24 percent those labor costs had 
skyrocketed at an annual rate of 45 percent in the final quarter 
of 1987 on a massive employment surge 
however after taking inflation into account as measured by 
relative changes in total output and prices the wage gains 
yielded not a penny more of purchasing power 
the 09 percent improvement in productivity for nonfarm 
businesses which are responsible for about threefourths of the 
nations economic activity is only slightly ahead of the 08 
percent increase for all of 1987 
earlier figures had shown a 03 percent increase in the fourth 
quarter of last year but those were revised in todays report to a 
1 percent deterioration 
manufacturing which still accounts for about onefourth of the 
countrys gross national product continued to lead the effort in 
restoring us competitiveness 
manufacturers productivity increased at an annual rate of 29 
percent in the first quarter with a 43 percent increase in output 
on only a 13 percent increase in the number of hours worked in the 
nations factories 
for the first time since early 1986 factory workers actually 
kept ahead of inflation 
nominal wage gains averaging 39 percent annually in the first 
quarter the biggest jump in about three years increased the 
purchasing power of manufacturing employees by onehalf of 1 
percent after dropping 22 percent in 1987 
it also raised the labor costs associated with each item coming 
off the assembly lines by 1 percent compared with a nearly 2 
percent drop in labor costs in 1987 
