<TEXT>
four senators who hold sway over nasa spending 
say they will not authorize a 700 million scheme to lease an 
unmanned robot space factory from the private developers who would 
build and own it 
in a letter to the national aeronautics and space 
administration the senators said that neither the reagan 
administration nor nasa has done the studies to justify such an 
expenditure they directed the space agency to contract with the 
national academy of sciences to undertake a thorough and 
independent review to be completed by next march 
president reagan proposed that the government agree in advance 
to lease 70 percent of the socalled commercially developed space 
facility at 140 million a year for five years 
the private facility would be carried into orbit by the space 
shuttle and revisited periodically by astronauts who would service 
the factory and bring back its products 
the committee feels that a 700 million budget commitment 
especially in these times of severe budget constraints should be 
based on a detailed assessment of the nations microgravity 
research requirements and capabilities the senators told nasa 
administrator james c fletcher 
the letter dated last thursday was signed by the chairman of 
the senate commerce committee sen ernest f hollings dsc the 
panels ranking republican sen john danforth of missouri and by 
senators donald w riegle dmich and larry pressler rsc the 
chairman and ranking republican member of the space subcommittee 
the administration has sought the facility which could be ready 
for launch in the next decade as an interim facility to be used 
until the proposed manned space station is in orbit in the mid to 
late1990s 
