the bureau of indian affairs concerned about 
the weak education its schools are delivering is asking indians 
how it should strengthen the instruction of their children 
a new report from the bureau documenting test scores worse than 
those of 79 percent of the nations students calls on tribal school 
boards councils and others to consider an improvement strategy 
emphasizing strong principals held accountable for results 
of the bureau districts what it calls agencies only one 
showed children scoring above the national median for their grade 
tribal leaders and school boards have had access to their own 
scores before but the new report commissioned by ross swimmer 
assistant interior secretary for indian affairs provides the first 
opportunity for one tribe or area to compare its standing with 
another said an interior department official who discussed the 
document on condition of anonymity 
the authors conceded that it will be difficult to install new 
leaders and revitalizing a system that appears too often to be 
going through the motions 
calling the system in dire need of improvment the report 
said it is no secret that bia education is today an organization 
lacking in a sense of direction 
its most productive members often feel that any successes they 
achieve occur despite the system rather than with its support 
collegiality the act of putting aside vested interests and 
working for the good of the whole is found in americas best 
educational institutions but is often missing in the bia system 
where administrators are sometimes more interested in shoring up 
and expanding their administrative domain 
drawing on research findings being promoted by the department of 
education the report said 
it is the principal above all who needs to insist on high 
standards of achievement for students and teachers and to 
communicate the firm expectation that these standards will be met 
some bia teachers seem to begin with the expectation that their 
students will do poorly 
the bureau educates 37917 indian students about 10 percent of 
the nations young indians and about as many pupils as the public 
schools of oklahoma city okla or corpus christi texas about 30 
percent attend boarding schools and about 30 percent are in schools 
run by tribes under contract with the bureau 
few of the students even approached national averages on 
standard tests administered in the 19851986 school year 
