<TEXT>
brussels belgium five parties reached agreement monday on 
forming a new government which would end an impasse that began 
when the last coalition fell in a language dispute oct 19 
wilfried martens prime minister of the last government and now 
serving as caretaker also would lead the new coalition 
jeanluc dehaene a dutchspeaking christian democrat who spent 
more than four months negotiating an accord said he expected 
approval at meetings of the five parties thursday involved are the 
dutch and frenchspeaking wings of the socialists and christian 
democrats and the nationalist dutchspeaking volksunie 
keeping martens as head of the 35th belgian government since 
world war ii is the best guarantee for continued stability 
dehaene told reporters he said the coalition should be installed 
within three weeks 
it will continue the previous centerright administrations 
economic austerity program including tax reform and reductions in 
public spending he said 
the most immediate problems to which government policies must 
respond are those of employment and the budget he said 
the martens coalition dissolved oct 19 in a linguistic dispute 
between wings of both his christian democrats and conservative 
coalition parties from flanders the dutchspeaking northern half 
of belgium and wallonia where the language is french 
in the dec 13 elections the government parties won only 110 of 
the 212 parliament seats a loss of five and negotiations on 
forming a new government have continued since 
if the fiveparty coalition comes together it will control 150 
seats well above the twothirds legislative majority needed for 
constitutional amendments that would increase regional autonomy in 
flanders and wallonia 
dehaene social affairs minister in the last government began 
negotiations with the five parties jan 22 after coalition talks by 
two socialist politicians failed 
belgiums population is split between 45 million people who 
speak french and 55 million to whom dutch is native 
