<TEXT>
us exports and japanese imports both boomed 
last year while the united states slowed the pace of its buying 
abroad and japanese sales actually declined the international 
monetary fund reported monday 
but the united states still bought 1737 billion worth of goods 
more than it sold up from 1698 billion the year before 
japans surplus dropped to 804 billion from 832 billion in 
1986 
dollar figures reflect the drop in the value of the us 
currency in terms of the yen as well as the actual amount of the 
goods traded this drop reduces the value of foreign sales and 
increases the cost of imports in japan and west germany the 
effect is the opposite imports are cheaper and sales bring in less 
money in terms of dollars 
the drop of the dollar was so large that it outweighed the 
increase of us exports in the final balance at the end of march 
the dollar was worth 865 percent less than it was 12 months 
earlier the fund calculates 
in terms of actual goods sold us exports rose 132 percent 
for the year against only 1 percent in 1986 imports still grew by 
22 percent but that was much less than the 109 percent of the 
year before 
japanese imports rose by 61 percent in the first nine months of 
1987 a considerable increase though less than the 128 percent of 
1986 exports dropped by 24 percent more than double the 1 
percent of 1986 
the fund calls these real adjustments in trade patterns but 
it notes that trade remains way out of balance 
west germany raised its imports by 52 percent somewhat less 
than the 59 percent increase the previous year but it also 
increased its foreign sales by 28 percent considerably more than 
the 09 percent rise in 1986 
the germans increased their trade surplus to 658 billion in 
1987 from 522 billion a year earlier 
taken as a whole the 21 countries that the fund calls 
industrial bought more than they sold to poorer areas 854 
billion worth up from 661 billion in 1986 neither the soviet 
union nor any other country with a communust government is included 
in this category 
for poorer countries the funds monthly imf memorandum 
emphasized the rise in prices paid by consumers 
inflation rose sharply in the developing countries in 1987 
led by a sharp acceleration of inflation in the western 
hemisphere it reported 
in the americas the rise was 1188 percent up from 822 in 
1986 but still below the 1614 rise in 1985 
the third worlds three biggest debtors also had the biggest 
price rises 2297 percent in brazil 1318 percent in mexico and 
1313 percent in argentina 
for the funds 130 poor countries inflation was put at 401 
percent compared with 293 percent in 1986 the rise was moderated 
by the record in asia where the rate was held to 69 percent up 
from only 54 percent in a year 
