supplied the book lyrics and direction and keith herrmann who 
wrote the music have gone to a short story by arthur schnitzler 
and a play by jules renard for their double bill 
its the curtain raiser the little comedy that proves to 
be the more agreeable the witty schnitzler short story set in 
turnofthecentury vienna adapts well to the stage the tale is 
told in the form of letters to old friends the format is not as 
confining as one might think because the missives are acted out by 
the two main characters 
the letter writers alfred and josefine are bored jaded 
members of the viennese upper crust they toss away lovers like 
yesterdays strudel for a little excitement the two of them go 
slumming and meet in a park he pretends to be a penniless poet 
she becomes a poor shopgirl poverty attracts at least for a while 
reality finally sets in and both are relieved to discover they 
are from the same wealthy social set the two lovers will get 
married but dont expect the union to last they both say at the 
fadeout 
harman keeps the slender story spinning and although his rhymes 
are often predictable they at least illuminate the characters or 
advance the tightly focused plot herrmanns music has the 
appropriate old world charm especially a lilting title song the 
little comedy is a crisp confection topped with just the right 
amount of sour cream 
but things turn soggy in act 2 a moist little musical called 
summer share the locale is a trendy hamptons beach house 
shared by two married couples monica is sams best friend even 
though they are married to other people so how long will it be 
before they have an affair well they think about it for a long 
time so do their mates and so does the audience left squirming 
while the two wouldbe lovers make up their minds 
the characters are sketched so skimpily that its impossible to 
work up interest in any of them especially after they keep 
insisting how wonderful their marriages are 
although summer share claims to be the more modern of the 
two shows it is also the more sentimental and shopworn the 
evening ends with the characters urging theatergoers to cherish 
your romantic notions 
scott bakula is an ingratiating handsome leading man hes 
rakish and debonair in the first musical pensive and appealing in 
the second as the unrepentant coquette alison fraser is 
perfection in the first act but the sappy material defeats her in 
the second musical deborah graham and robert hoshour are properly 
morose as the leftout spouses in act 2 
steven rubins modest settings are in keeping with the modest 
tone of the whole evening while steven jones costumes capture the 
spirit of both eras 
the musicals originally done last fall at a tiny 
offoffbroadway theater have undergone some reworking in their 
transfers to the larger helen hayes summer share received the 
biggest rehab but the fixing didnt do much good 
romance romance offers two looks at love one lively the 
other leaden stay until intermission and youll have an 
entertaining time 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
what other critics said 
in the new york times walter goodman said romance romance 
lately the littlest musical offoffbroadway has made it uptown 
in a slightly enhanced production that loses nothing of the charm 
and intelligence of the original in a broadway season so full 
of pretentiousness this show is delightfully small scale 
howard kissel in the daily news wrote for all its virtues 
romance romance is a show that keeps you at a distance 
ultimately the material is arch and clever you dont feel youre 
rediscovering simple affection rather you feel youre being let 
in on a joke 
in the new york post clive barnes said just as the evening 
is a pair of sketches the shows joys and disappointments are 
mixed barnes praised the two leads scott bakula and alison 
fraser but added the sad thing is that the musical or at 
least the music doesnt really support them 
</TEXT>
