<TEXT>
the united states on monday urged the polish 
government to negotiate with its labor unions and to refrain from 
using force against striking workers 
the current strikes in poland demonstrate more clearly than 
ever that successful economic reform and recovery require genuine 
dialogue between the government and society state department 
spokesman charles redman said in our view such dialogue must 
allow for the expression of working peoples concerns and rights 
redman added that the use of force cannot contribute to 
national reconciliation 
the solidarity trade union movement complained of exceptional 
brutality by police in clashes with protesters sunday in poland 
thousands of polish workers are striking to back demands for 
increased pay to offset price hikes of 42 percent caused by the 
governments austerity program the weeklong work stoppages are 
described as the worst labor unrest in poland since the communist 
government suspended solidarity in december 1981 
redman said the united states supports the polish governments 
economic reform program and is willing to help in its 
implementation but he added that such help is feasible only if 
the difficult economic changes needed are supported by a broad 
spectrum of polish society 
the reforms that began in 1986 have included a thinning of the 
government bureaucracy and encouragement of private enterprise 
one us official said the reagan administration was willing to 
help poland if agreement is reached between the government and 
the unions by supporting its loan requests to the world bank and 
the international monetary fund 
poland owes some 40 billion the largest chunk to west germany 
and a significant sum to the united states the official said 
the united states which is the largest contributor to both 
institutions would be willing to support loan programs if poland 
is serious about future reforms said the official who spoke 
only on condition he not be named 
the united states improved its ties with poland after the polish 
government released all political prisoners at the end of 1986 
cultural and economic ties were restored and both countries 
exchanged ambassadors in march 
