<TEXT>
britain will reconsider the use of special british 
forces license plates on its military vehicles because of fears 
they mark servicemen as ira targets a government minister promised 
monday 
the irish republican army which killed three british servicemen 
and injured three in the netherlands on sunday has threatened to 
kill more british forces members abroad 
armed forces minister ian stewart was asked in a british 
broadcasting corp radio interview whether use of the plates would 
be looked at as part of the security review promised sunday by 
defense secretary george younger 
yes it certainly will he said there are a number of 
aspects we want to look into and that is certainly one of them 
the ministry of defense said the use of a special block of 
registration numbers was an administrative convenience for a 
group of temporary residents abroad but several british lawmakers 
have criticized the plates as a giveaway to terrorists 
the daily telegraph on monday quoted an unidentified ministry of 
defense spokeman as saying that all cars owned by military 
personnel and their dependents in west germany are registered as 
british forces vehicles bearing license plates that are not the 
normal german civilian ones 
it would be a very small but effective change to put all 
number plates on the civilian register said terrorism expert dr 
richard clutterbuck of exeter university as quoted by the daily 
telegraph on monday 
sundays victims of a shooting and a bomb attack were senior 
aircraftsmen in the royal air force regiment which guards air 
bases based in west germany they were visiting dutch discotheques 
and bars just across the border 
the ira claimed responsibility for sundays attacks with a 
statement through the irish republican publicity bureau in dublin 
since launching its violent campaign to end british rule in 
northern ireland in 1969 the ira has killed 392 british soldiers 
