<DOCNO> AP880502-0178 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the virus that causes aids can invade the bone 
marrow and infect cells there even when the virus cannot be 
detected in blood samples a national institutes of health 
scientist said monday 
anthony s fauci director of the national institute of allergy 
and infectious diseases a part of the nih said he and other 
researchers found that the bone marrow which is the bodys 
bloodmaking organ can become a quiet haven for the deadly aids 
virus 
our study shows that it the bone marrow can be a 
reservoir he said it the aids virus can reside in the 
marrow but not be detected in the peripheral blood 
the finding adds to the types of cells in the body known to be 
attacked by the virus that causes aids or acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome 
in addition the finding demonstrates just how challenging it 
will be to develop an antiviral drug or vaccine to defeat the aids 
virus said fauci in order to effect a cure some way will have to 
be found to seek out and destroy the virus wherever it hides 
it is going to be very difficult to eliminate each and every 
viral particle in the body said fauci because the virus takes 
refuge in cell groups and apparently can live there in a latent 
state for years without causing any clinical signs of infection 
the virus called the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv was 
first thought to infect only tlymphocyte cells that have a protein 
on the cell surface called cd4 researchers later learned that the 
virus also could invade some brain cells and another type of blood 
cell the monocyte 
now said fauci researchers have confirmed that the virus also 
can reside in the cells of the bone marrow this is important 
because the bone marrow is the factory that makes the various types 
of blood cells 
in routine blood examinations the test for aids involves a 
search for antibodies to the virus since the virus itself often is 
not found in the blood 
fauci said it is yet to be absolutely confirmed but there is a 
suggestion that the hiv lives in a type of bone marrow cell that is 
the immature form of the monocyte and unlike the tlymphocyte the 
virus does not kill the bone marrow cell but reproduces within the 
cell 
researchers are still trying to understand what causes the 
latent virus to suddenly start reproducing and become an active 
infection after living in the body quietly for years fauci said 
there is some suggestion that the triggering mechanism may be the 
response of the immune system to other infections this may start a 
process that in effect turns on the virus 
fauci reported on the research during a lecture at a joint 
meeting of three organizations of physicians and clinical 
researchers 
aids is a contagious fatal disease that kills by attacking the 
tcell lymphocytes a key part in the bodys immune system when 
the tcells are killed the body is unable to protect itself 
against disease and death usually results from opportunistic 
infections 
the aids virus most often is spread through close contact with 
blood blood products or semen from infected persons 
as of april 21 aids had been diagnosed in about 59500 
americans of whom more than half or about 33000 have died since 
june 1981 according to the federal centers for disease control no 
one is known to have recovered from aids 
</TEXT>
