<TEXT>
a twoweek sitin at a wesleyan 
university administration building ended monday after 110 students 
were arrested for blocking entrances to protest the schools 
investments in companies doing business in south africa 
middletown police put students on three buses to take them away 
from the building that houses the office of university president 
colin campbell about six hours after the blockade began none 
resisted arrest 
the blockade was obviously an escalation said bobby wayne 
clark a university spokesman 
the students were charged with creating a public disturbance and 
were all released on their own recognizance police said 
police intervention was sought only after the administration 
tried but failed to resolve the conflict internally putting the 
issue before the student judiciary board clark said 
the student board concluded that the protesters actions had 
crossed the line of tolerability and had become an invasion 
of the rights of other individuals to free access to a university 
facility 
clark said however that it was likely the cases against the 
students would be resolved within the university and that the 
charges would not be prosecuted 
the protest monday marked the second time in the last four years 
that there has been a mass arrest of students at wesleyan over the 
schools investment policies 
a spokesman for the protesters said they were dissatisfied with 
campbells response to their demands in all of his statements he 
has barely even begun to acknowledge that we are here said john 
stamm a senior from boston 
the antiapartheid protesters had been peacefully conducting a 
sitin to protest the private liberal arts colleges investment 
policies the school has about 103 million of its 240 million 
endowment invested in companies that conduct some form of business 
in south africa 
the students members of the divest now coalition of groups 
opposed to south africas racist policies decided to take a more 
militant approach sunday after the school failed to meet their 
divestment demands 
the coalition demanded that the university trustees social 
implications subcommittee open its process to include student 
representatives that the subcommittee recommend total divestment 
in a final report by may 8 and that the trustees hold a special 
meeting to vote for total divestment before the end of the school 
term classes end wednesday and exams end may 17 
but campbell told the students sunday that the subcommittee 
would continue to meet privately he promised that it would open 
its meeting on campus tuesday for about an hour to student 
representatives 
