<TEXT>
some representatives of former dalkon shield 
users urged rejection monday of the latest reorganization plan 
involving ah robins manufacturer of the defective contraceptive 
device that injured thousands of women 
after an agonizing decisionmaking and education process we 
have found that the plan is unfair inadequate and contrary to the 
law karen hicks founder of the dalkon shield information 
network told a news conference 
however another representative of the victims atlantabased 
attorney guerry r thornton jr said the plan offered the best 
deal yet for the more than 196000 women harmed by the intrauterine 
device 
the 32 billion reorganization plan the sixth plan developed 
since robins filled for chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1985 is part of 
the manhattanbased american home products corps agreement to 
take over the beleaguered company the 32 billion plan includes 
23 billion to be put in a trust fund for the victims 
the plan was presented in a mailing last week to all claimants 
against robins including the 196000 former dalkon shield users 
who have injury claims pending against robins as well as banks and 
stockholders 
all claimants are to mail in ballots by july 11 with the final 
resolution of the case scheduled for july 18 
in order for the plan to be approved under an arrangement set up 
in march by us district judge robert r merhige jr at least 
twothirds of the voters in each class of creditors must vote 
yes 
hicks said the courtdesignated dalkon shield committee assigned 
to represent the women who had used the device estimated that 
claims against the manufacturer would range from 42 billion to 7 
billion 
she contended that under the reorganization plan stockholders 
and other creditors would immediately be paid 100 cents on the 
dollar but that women filing claims against the company may receive 
only 35 cents to 50 cents on the dollar after administrative costs 
have been deducted the plan also gives the fund until the year 
2008 to pay the women 
the claimants are carrying the entire burden of all the 
unknowns in this case were being treated unfairly relative to 
other people hicks said 
ah robins spokesman rosco puckett said the company was 
satisfied with the plan which provides full funding for the 
amount of money the court has announced as needed for compensation 
and related administrative costs this is a plan of consensus which 
was endorsed by all executive committees 
the dalkon shield committee fought us tooth and nail for all 
32 months and they believe this is adequate it provides the 
full amount of money to satisfy the court he said 
hicks said that if the funds prove to be inadequate the former 
users have no legal recourse to sue the manufacturer or aetna 
casualty amp surety co the company that insured robins 
she contended that the plan violates bankruptcy law requiring 
that priority be given to settling claims like those of the former 
dalkon shield users before any stockholders are paid 
thornton who has been campaigning actively for adoption of the 
settlement said hicks was right about the law but he said the 
courts would uphold the arrangement because the judge found that it 
was fair 
if approved the award plus interest and approximately 300 
million from aetna brings the total to 27 billion a figure 
thornton said the victims couldnt get if they sold all of robins 
property on the open market 
the aetna funds come from cash payment in the bankruptcy suit 
and another 75 million settlement from a separate class action 
suit alleging the company had conspired with robins to withhold 
information about the dalkon shield thornton said 
for some people understandably you could get the us gross 
national product have ah robins behind bars and that would not 
be enough thornton said 
thornton said it would take another three or four years to match 
the offer from american home and said many of his clients were 
nearing the end of their childbearing years and desperately 
needed the money to finance infertility treatments they just dont 
have the time it would take to get this again 
 
</TEXT>
