a jamaican citizen employed at the 
guantanamo naval base in cuba was charged with manslaughter after 
the car he was driving smashed into a navy van killing six people 
and injuring four others authorities said monday 
the navy filed six charges of vehicular manslaughter against 
carlton bonner who is under guard at the base hospital in 
guantanamo said lt russ greer a spokesman at atlantic fleet 
headquarters in norfolk va 
six people were killed in the fiery wreck saturday night 
including the driver of the van and five sailors from the 
norfolkbased uss inchon a helicopter and troop carrier that is 
undergoing refresher training in the caribbean three other sailors 
from the inchon were seriously injured 
greer identified the five sailors killed as seaman recruit 
michael w bauman of clovis nm storekeeperseaman brent d 
jervey of gainesville fla boatswains mate 1st class john f 
piper of monongahela pa seaman jeffrey m rais of cincinnati 
and petty officer 1st class frederick w vilmar of saginaw mich 
the van driver was identified as michael chambers also a 
jamaican national who worked at the base supply department as an 
accounting clerk and had been a civilian employee of the navy since 
1983 greer said 
three injured sailors were evacuated sunday to the brooke army 
burn center in san antonio texas a spokeswoman for the center who 
would not give her name said they were in critical condition 
they were identified as aircraft storekeeper recruit demetric l 
cofield 30 of harrisburg pa ships serviceman prentice d 
johnson 21 of indianapolis and fireman darren stevenson 30 of 
chester pa 
