<TEXT>
leaders of the nicaraguan contra rebels met monday 
amid signs that their troops are running short of supplies and some 
field commanders are demanding removal of their military chief 
contra directors polled their top military officers monday over 
the fate of col enrique bermudez confirmed rebel spokesman jorge 
rosales 
we are working on obtaining signatures of all the field 
commanders said rosales 
sources close to the contras said some of the five directors 
were expected to demand bermudezs firing at the meeting in miami 
in honduras walter calderon lopez known as cmdr tono gave 
interviews over the weekend saying as many as 30 senior contra 
commanders had signed a petition demanding bermudezs ouster 
bermudez has to go tono said the movement cannot 
continue with him in charge 
he said bermudez a former colonel in the hated national guard 
of deposed dictator anastasio somoza debayle has recently been 
surrounding himself with other former guardsmen 
and tono accused bermudez of condoning and possibly 
participating in skimming profits from us military aid 
the controversy over bermudez follows a week of reports that 
contra director adolfo calero had led an unsuccessful move to fire 
the military chief running up against the opposition of fellow 
director aristides sanchez 
sources said sanchez has indicated privately that if bermudez is 
fired he may quit the directorate of the nicaraguan resistance as 
the contras are formally known sanchez is considered the most 
hardline of the five directors and has the closest ties to the 
field troops 
the battle over bermudez was not the contras only worry 
however 
their soldiers situation has worsened as the ruling sandinistas 
have refused to allow food and nonlethal supplies to reach rebels 
the contras accuse the sandinistas of reneging on the agreement 
signed in sapoa nicaragua in march that said the aid would be 
allowed in during negotiations the contras issued minutes of that 
meeting monday aimed at showing the sandinistas had agreed to the 
aid 
rosales said the sandinistas are now demanding concessions in 
return for the food and supplies 
they are trying to blackmail us with hunger said rosales 
it is a difficult situation the aid must begin immediately 
the sandinistas offered to have the international committee of 
the red cross deliver the humanitarian aid but the contras 
insisted they have the right to say who delivers it and they see 
red cross as sympathetic to sandinistas 
the agreement says the rebels may receive aid through a neutral 
organization once they are in the ceasefire zones 
when the rebel leaders returned from nicaragua on sunday after 
the latest round of unsuccessful peace talks with the sandinistas 
contra director pedro joaquin chamorro bitterly criticized the 
handling of the aid issue 
they are hinging the entire ceasefire agreement on how goods 
will be delivered instead of on the democratization of nicaragua 
