editors note with foreign investment at record levels and 
tourists swarming over the countryside the mediterranean nations 
of southern europe are starting to catch up with their 
industrialized neighbors to the north there are some persistent 
problems to be sure but one chief of state predicts the region 
will become the motor of the european community 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after decades of instability and stagnation 
europes southern nations are enjoying a surge of economic growth 
that hints at a potential americanstyle sun belt in the old world 
following world war ii a succession of shaky governments led 
italy while spain portugal greece and turkey were ruled by 
dictatorships or militarybacked governments their economies grew 
by fits and starts 
now for the first time all five countries three of them led 
by englishspeaking economists have governments or coalitions 
likely to lead them into the 1990s growth rates are generally 
higher than the european norm and foreign investment has reached 
record levels 
the center of gravity of europe has moved south says 
portuguese premier anibal cavaco silva whose social democrats won 
a landslide victory in the 1987 elections 
the southern nations will now become the motor of the european 
community 
in the 1980s greece spain and portugal joined the 12nation 
european community marking a more forceful mediterranean presence 
in the trade bloc with turkey knocking on the door for membership 
the european community would like to turn the south of europe 
into a developed area resembling the northern countries says 
antonio la pergola italys sicilianborn harvardeducated 
minister for european community relations this could create a 
sun belt like in the united states in this area 
the brusselsbased community forecasts that the population in 
its southern tier will grow faster than in its northern areas 
industrialization drawing its manpower from the higher birth 
rates may thus trigger economic growth similar to that in the 
united states that led to a migration from the northeast to the 
southeastern sun belt states 
symbolizing the areas new dynamism are spains 
multimilliondollar preparations for the worlds fair in seville in 
1992 and the summer olympics in barcelona the same year 
greece and turkey are cooling their disputes over aegean sea oil 
rights and the mediterranean island of cyprus to focus instead on 
streamlining their oldfashioned economies 
and italy the sick man of europe in the 1970s has become one 
of its economic superstars and now claims to have replaced britain 
as the fifth richest western nation nowadays 76 percent of 
italian households have a car compared with britains 58 percent 
while 81 percent have dishwashers against 77 percent for britain 
but smart cars and flashy clothes are not italys only visible 
signs of prosperity 
italian entrepreneurs were involved in 28 of 68 european mergers 
and takeovers completed over the past two years 
businessmen are anticipating an economic freeforall in 1992 
when common market currency and tariffs finally come down more 
than 320 million europeans will trade goods and services in a 
single market fulfilling the visionary plans of the communitys 
founders when they signed the treaty of rome in 1957 
among them is carlo de benedettti a 53yearold engineer who 
transformed the olivetti typewriter firm into a computer giant and 
is battling for control of the 166yearold societe generale de 
belgique belgiums largest holding company 
giovanni agnelli head of the fiat automakers italys largest 
private company is credited with spearheading italys economic 
revival in the early 1980s holdings controlled by the agnelli 
family range from communications and media properties food 
processing and biotech industries to mutual funds and robot makers 
illustrating newfound confidence in southern europe two leading 
west german banks deutschebank and bayerische vereinsbank last 
year took over italian branches of bankamerica and first national 
bank of chicago respectively 
although italys fiveparty coalition government still plays 
political musical chairs the economy purrs on 
two days after premier giovanni goria resigned on march 11 for 
the third time during his sevenmonth tenure the milan stock 
market recorded its largest gain since the start of the year 
joseph lapalombara a yale university professor argues in his 
book democracy italian style that italys most glaring problem 
political instability is more apparent than real and is in 
fact a positive measure of the countrys heady spirit for survival 
and change 
coming up fast on the west of the mediterranean rim are spain 
and portugal the eecs newest members both recorded 4 percent 
growth rates last year double the eec average contrasted with 
west germanys near zero growth last year 
portugal and spain form the area of greatest economic growth 
in the eec and are the countries that exhibit the best economic 
prospects for the next five years says pedropablo kuczynski a 
peruvian banker with first boston international 
in spain foreign investors last year poured 79 billion into 
the economy twice the 1986 amount to fund one of europes 
fasttrack economies moving toward what the spaniards call el 
horizonte 92 horizon 92 
i see an important new axis from turin to paris to madrid 
bringing the center of europe southward says juan luis cebrian 
the editor of madrids daily el pais 
spain and portugal are coming together in a way we would have 
thought unbelievable only a few years ago he says 
the barcelona olympic games and the seville worlds fair in 1992 
will create new housing hightech communications and rail and 
road networks at an estimated cost of 89 billion 
the streets of madrid are now choked with shiny new cars 
tripleparked auto sales increased by 29 percent last year 
according to the spanish association of automobile makers 
using skilled spanish labor at lower cost than in the united 
states american telephone amp telegraph co is building an advanced 
microchip plant near madrid and at some rchards in spain apple 
computers are used to keep track of the orange crop 
reaching across continents spain has signed a 3 billion accord 
with argentina to form jointventure companies financed by both 
countries 
