editors note he was introduced to music at the holiness 
church in birmingham ala and a catholic nun in wisconsin taught 
him to play the snare drum he would go on to play with such jazz 
greats as louis armstrong and benny goodman and eventually form his 
own band a halfcentury later lionel hampton is still on the 
road playing his kind of music 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
vibraphonist lionel hampton who just turned 75 
is leading a swinging band of 17 musicians mostly in their 20s 
following the beat of another generation 
were doing big business on the road says hamp as he is 
known to his friends we play every night we pack the house i 
dont have to play rock n roll i play what i always played like 
beat me daddy eight to the bar 
hampton who was in the first racially integrated group in jazz 
benny goodmans quartet wrote his most famous composition 
flying home in 1937 he estimates he has played it 300 times a 
year for 51 years and it still stops the show 
i like to play with this band says hampton who recruits 
his musicians from among college graduates who majored in jazz 
the guys are all interested everybody tries to play better than 
he played last night that makes it fun 
im trying to play better than i played last night too 
the band spent its annual stint in february at the university of 
idaho lionel hampton school of music where some 15000 high 
schoolers came to seminars it opened the jazzport at manhattans 
south street seaport with two twohour concerts on both april 1 and 
2 and played a benefit for jazz radio station wbgofm at town hall 
on april 7 
after a birthday bash at regines here on april 19 the band 
left the next day hamptons 75th birthday on a tour of germany 
france scandinavia austria switzerland and italy 
hampton who plans to campaign for the republicans will play 
jazz festivals this summer and appear at the hollywood bowl and 
disneyland hes invited to brazil for two weeks and on a jazz 
cruise for eight days 
the grin the unrestrained energy buoyant personality and 
showmanship are still hamptons hallmarks along with his melodic 
and swinging performing style 
when i was a kid i always wanted to put on a show he 
recalls i liked to get in the moonshine at night doing like im 
on the stage i always liked to be taking bows 
hampton who was born in louisville ky says that when his 
father joined the army his mother moved him to her family home in 
birmingham where he was raised by his grandmother 
we used to go to the holiness church every time the church 
door opened he recalls there was a swinging band there 
trumpets saxophones guitars we sat down in one of the front pews 
next to where the band was when the sister beating the bass drum 
would get happy and start up and down the aisles i took the 
mallets and started beating the bass drum it was my introduction 
to music 
not only has he stayed with music hampton says i also stayed 
with the bible and religion all the time 
a framed picture of his grandmother livinia morgan rests on 
the grand piano in hamptons manhattan apartment i was crazy 
about my grandmother he says 
when the family moved to chicago where the schools were tough 
his grandmother sent him to a roman catholic school in kenosha 
wis there a nun taught him how to play the snare drum and how to 
twirl the sticks toss and catch them 
back in chicago he joined les hites band as a drummer at age 
15 he followed hite to los angeles and two years later they 
auditioned to back louis armstrong at frank sebastians cotton club 
in los angeles 
louis liked us so well he took us recording with him 
hampton recalls there was a set of vibes in a corner louis 
said do you know how to play it move it out here in the middle 
of the floor and play something for me 
</TEXT>
