<TEXT>
the severed heads of a school principal 
and a journalist were left hanging in plastic bags in a town square 
set among lovely wooded hills their foreheads were smeared with 
vermilion a gurkha mark of revenge 
the killings in april were among the most brutal in the twoyear 
campaign by gurkhas famed as soldiers in the british and indian 
armies for the creation of a separate indian state called 
gurkhaland around this oncetranquil vacation retreat 
subash ghising 52yearold leader of the gurkha agitation has 
been negotiating with indian government officials but in an 
interview with the associated press he seemed in no mood to 
compromise 
we want blood for blood an eye for an eye and we will settle 
for nothing less than a homeland for the gurkhas he said at his 
wellguarded headquarters in darjeeling which also is famous for 
its tea 
so far ghisings repeated trips to new delhi have swayed indian 
officials to offer the gurkha area some governmental power and 
development funds but not to make it indias 26th state 
the killing goes on with at least 275 deaths recorded since the 
agitation started in april 1986 
some officials of west bengal state which now governs the area 
say privately the dispute has the potential to lead to more 
dangerous demands for a separate country as militant sikhs have 
done in punjab state 
the gurkhas who are indians of nepalese descent want 2250 
square miles around darjeeling an area slightly larger than 
delaware as a gurkha state within india they say their hilly 
homeland is different from the flatlands around the west bengals 
capital calcutta and that they are ethnically distinct from the 
bengalis 
the gurkhas say about 14 million gurkha people live around 
darjeeling and 46 million live elsewhere in india they first came 
here in the 1850s to make their way as soldiers or as workers on 
tea plantations 
ghising a former army corporal teacher and bantamweight boxer 
says government force can only aggravate the problem 
by provoking us by killing or wounding our men the 
government is creating wounded tigers he said you know what a 
wounded tiger does it hunts for men and devours them 
nowadays only police officers are seen at night outside the 
quaint old houses built by the british who developed darjeeling as 
a hill station 
fears have worsened since april 6 when school principal dileswar 
rais severed head was found in kalimpong 43 miles east of 
darjeeling he had kept his school open during a general strike 
called by gurkha militants 
the severed head of nirmal rai a reporter for a local 
newspaper was found at the same place april 12 the journalist 
who was not related to the principal was accused of being a police 
informer 
the governments response to the violence has been building up a 
force of more than 4000 security forces and paramilitary police 
who often open fire with mortars and machine guns 
we are fighting a very well entrenched enemy and the terrain 
is in their favor said raj kanojia a police superintendent in 
charge of antiinsurgency operations 
amid the violence the tea and tourist trades are suffering a 
backlash by marxistcontrolled unions has forced 30000 gurkha 
laborers to flee from tea estates to refugee camps in darjeeling 
and the adjoining state of sikkim 
gurkha insurgents have felled at least 2000 pine trees to block 
roads more than 600 homes have been burned by insurgents or 
marxists who support the calcutta government 
more than 250 government buildings have been set ablaze 
including two stations of the toy train built in 1879 by the 
british and so called for its tiny cars and narrowgauge track 
the gurkha campaign also has triggered fears for the security of 
the seven strategically important northeastern states near china 
with whom india has a longstanding border dispute 
the northeast an area about the size of colorado is connected 
to the main part of india by a narrow land corridor called the 
siliguri neck in the envisoned gurkhaland 
ghising the gurkha leader now brushed aside the question of 
secession 
we are indians and we will remain indians he said 
but ghising who also is the author of more than 20 racy 
potboiler novels in the nepali language made it clear he is not 
going to give in without achieving his goals 
he sits in an office guarded by toughlooking gurkas with their 
traditonal curved 14inch kukri knives behind him is a green 
gurkhaland flag emblazoned with a kukri and three stars 
he reeled off his demands 
recognition of nepali as an official indian language 
more government jobs for gurkhas 
better education and more industry 
if we do not get statehood for gurkhaland the indian 
government will regret it he added they have seen only a 
flash of gurkha retaliation gurkha courage gurkha dedication but 
if we are pushed we will start a full scale nonstop 
retaliation 
about 48000 retired gurkha soldiers live in darjeeling and 
indian officials fear they could join ghisings campaign 
above the town a giant graffiti painted on a mountain slope 
shows blood dripping from a kukri knife 
below it reads welcome to gurkhaland 
