<TEXT>
this city nelson algren once said has 
literally become my trade 
algren the winner of the first national book award lived among 
the ethnic patches of the northwest side of chicago bringing to 
life the roar of the elevated trains and recording in his mind and 
in notebooks the travails of the people 
he hung out in the police precincts seedy bars and brothels 
drug addicts gamblers and migrant workers had his ear 
the night often was his turf and his fiction breathed the night 
it isnt hard to love a town for its greater and its lesser 
towers algren wrote but you never truly love it till you can 
love its alleys too 
the city he loved didnt always return the sentiment 
poles offended with his sketches of the citys underbelly in 
never come morning pressured some library branches to keep the 
book out of circulation algren and his literary companions 
maintained 
but today seven years after he died at age 72 in sag harbor 
ny theres a romance brewing and it might finally stick 
a large exhibition room at the librarys downtown cultural 
center is the setting for writing in the first person nelson 
algren a rich tribute to a master of urban realism 
first edition books and original manuscripts are paired with 
algrens first stabs at writing including handwritten short 
stories a mock newspapers front page and summaries of 
neighborhood baseball games 
his army draft card is displayed with his honorable discharge 
as well as his detroit birth certificate march 28 1909 and 
papers showing his name change from nelson ahlgren abraham to 
nelson algren 
pictures and personal letters document his affair with french 
philosopher simone de beauvoir who accompanied him on trips down 
the mississippi river and to other countries 
algren admired ernest hemingway and the affection was mutual 
you should not read it unless you can take a punch 
hemingway says in a wellworn letter offering his endorsement for 
an upcoming book 
mr algren hemingway wrote boy you are good 
the exhibit which opened in late february was scheduled to run 
through may 21 but has been extended for three weeks most of the 
items were purchased from local collectors or are on loan from ohio 
state university which has the largest algren archive 
besides the exhibit there also have been public readings 
hundreds turned out to hear pulitzer prize winner studs terkel 
another product of chicagos literary school of realism and a close 
friend of algren read from algrens books including the poetic 
chicago city on the make 
he was a wheel on fire terkel recalled in a interview i 
like the idea that he was honored its time he was given his 
place 
algren who moved to chicago from detroit when he was 3 
graduated from the university of illinois with a journalism degree 
in 1931 his first published works mostly short stories stemmed 
from his experiences in the south where he traveled by freight 
train after college 
algren said he once wandered into a texas college and began 
typing a story on an unattended typewriter he decided to take the 
typewriter with him to chicago to finish the story but was 
arrested for theft and served five months in jail 
back in illinois he was an editor for the works progress 
administration from 193640 finally never come morning about 
a polish prizefighter tagged with a murder charge was published in 
1942 
it was a book that rankled polish civic groups for its gritty 
descriptions of life in their chicago neighborhoods 
he was never a coffee table man terkel said referring to 
algrens books 
in 1947 the american academy of arts and letters awarded him 
1000 in recognition for never come morning and the 
rockefeller foundation granted him 1000 to work on a new novel 
arguably his best the man with the golden arm 
algren received the first national book award in 1950 for the 
man with the golden arm a harrowing tale about frankie machine 
a chicago card dealer back from the war with a 35pound monkey 
on his back morphine addiction 
otto preminger made the book into a movie starring frank 
sinatra but preminger and algren fought fiercely over the 
production and the bitter hollywood experience was one the author 
would never forget 
another book a walk on the wild side also was transferred 
to the big screen starring jane fonda 
he had his detractors conservative critics hit algren for what 
they considered his penchant for glorifying hustlers hookers and 
hobos one once dismissed him as the bard of the stumblebum 
academics the english departments had become the arbiters of 
literature terkel said nelson was never one who was in their 
favor he sort of put them down and they knew it they reciprocated 
by making him a nonperson now hes pretty much a person and thats 
kind of good 
by the early 1970s algren had traveled to southeast asia and 
the far east writing dispatches for magazines and developing more 
books at the same time his ties to chicago began to diminish 
in 1973 he left for good 
but anyone who 12 years earlier had read his afterword to 
chicago city on the make could have predicted the move the 
city that was once a writers town he said was becoming just 
another town 
chicago has progressed culturally from being the second city 
to being the secondhand city he wrote the vital cog in our 
culture now is not the artist but the middleman whose commercial 
status lends art the aura of status when he acquires a collection 
of originals 
the word culture now means nothing more than approved it 
isnt what is exhibited so much that matters as where that being 
where one meets the people who matter 
terkel tried to explain to love a city you have to smack it 
around too it was the ambivalent feeling he had 
algren moved to paterson nj to cover the murder case of 
boxer rubin hurricane carter a novel based on the case the 
devils stocking was published posthumously in 1983 
he settled in sag harbor ny and died relatively poor a few 
weeks before his may 1981 induction into the prestigious american 
academy and institute of arts and letters 
money was an irritating subject to algren authors with less 
talent were wealthy he complained and hollywood producers reaped 
millions without spreading the credit to creators 
but in an interview published in 1964 algren seemed to suggest 
that writing good fiction not collecting cash was his goal 
i think anybody anybody if given the choice would always 
take the privilege of having his work wanted by other people rather 
than the privilege of having more money than anybody 
</TEXT>
