<TEXT>
phillips petroleum co said monday it 
has designed a plan it hopes will ease employees jitters about a 
possible takeover 
the work force stabilization plan approved by the board of 
directors last week would provide qualified employees with 
severance pay and other benefits should they be terminated without 
cause within two years of a takeover 
chairman cj silas said the plan had been under consideration 
for some time and was not in response to any anticipated takeover 
attempt 
phillips has been mentioned frequently as a takeover 
candidate and the board has been concerned that such speculation 
is affecting our ability to retain and motivate employees and 
therefore how well were able to perform for our current 
shareholders silas said 
phillips fought off unfriendly takeover attempts in 1984 and 
1985 partly as a result of costs incurred in those battles 
phillips has reduced its workforce by nearly onefourth 
the protection plan includes enhanced severance pay of up to two 
years based on years of service retirement benefits home purchase 
provisions and extension of medical dental and life insurance 
benefits 
the plan covers eligible longtime phillips employees on us 
payrolls who are terminated without cause within two years of the 
trigger date or employees who resign after a material loss of 
position salary or benefits 
