<TEXT>
a us trade delegation demanded 
monday that south korea open its domestic markets to us goods and 
end restrictive trade practices to help ease the american trade 
deficit 
peter allgier assistant us trade representative made the 
demand at the start of a threeday trade meeting with south korean 
officials which opened in seoul on monday 
south korean officials said allgier chief of the 19member us 
delegation asked south korea to slash its growing trade surplus 
with the united states by cutting tariffs and dismantling various 
import and sales restrictions 
hwang dooyoung head of the 19member south korean delegation 
explained seouls efforts to solve the problem and presented a 
detailed schedule to open its market the officials said 
the officials declined to disclose details however 
the seoul meeting the officials said will devote its first day 
session to discussions on south koreas high import tariffs and 
future plans to open its market for such us services and goods as 
advertising beer and wine 
the two sides will spend the second day discussing washingtons 
demand for retroactive protection of the us intellectual property 
rights the officials said 
the third will go for talks on eashing south koreas alleged 
restrictions on the sale of us cigarettes insurance and 
agricultural products they said 
the seoul meeting came after a series of bilateral talks on 
solving the issues had failed the united is threatening to 
retaliate unless south korea cuts its trade surplus with the united 
states which reached 95 billion last year 
